# Removing outliers

def remove_outliers(red_wine,sd): 
    from scipy import stats
    '''
    Creating a function to remove our outliers. These outliers are used defined as a value that is SOME 
#standard deviations from the mean value

red_wine is the dataset and sd is HOW MANY standard deviations we'll consider as the limit for the
measurement become an outlier value
'''
    return(red_wine[(np.abs(stats.zscore(red_wine)) < sd).all(axis=1)])

Such as asked in the statement of the question, here we tried to remove what we call outliers, points that may disturb our following applications

B. Principal component analysis (PCA)¶

Now we are going to perform a principal component analysis on our data considering all the features together (p = 12) and with the normalized data with zero mean and unit variance. This normalization means that there are no distortions in our analyzes due to the difference in magnitude orders of the features and their different units of measurement.

We know that in this case the points that are close express a positive correlation (similar behavior) and points that are very distant have the opposite correlation. However, as we saw that each eigenvector retains little information, we cannot infer that these few parameters perfectly describe the reasons for the quality of the wines.

C. Multivariate linear regression¶

Our objective is to apply Multivariate linear regression and the ideia is to fit the data with an hyperplane, to do so, we considered a linear model such as $$\hat{y} = \sum \beta_{j}x_{j} + \alpha $$

However, we did not want to have a bias element, and by setting the mean value as 0 we are able to get $$\hat{y} = \sum \beta_{j}x_{j} $$

When we are programming and we work with a high amount of data, it may seems very interesting to use the matrix notation. All the data can be represented by:

  • N × p matrix $X_{ij}$ of $p=11$ features that we consider as inputs.
  • N-dimensional vector $Y_{i}$ representing the quality

We can write the loss function as and use the matrix notation:

$$\mathcal{L} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i}^N ( Y_{i} - \sum_{j}^p \beta_{j}X_{ij})^{2} = \frac{1}{N} (Y- X\beta)^{T}(Y- X\beta) $$

If we derivates the loss function and equalizes it to zero we will be able to get:

$$\hat{\beta} = (X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T}Y $$

and the $R^{2}$ coefficient for the case with zero mean and $\alpha=0$ is:

$$ R^{2} = 1 - \frac{\overline{(y - \hat{\beta}x)^{2}}}{\overline{y^{2}}} $$

$R^{2} \in [0, 1]$ is often called by coefficient of determination and it can be considered as a measure of the goodness-of-fit, the closest to one, the better our fit will be.

We started by setting the mean of the features to zero as asked

In [21]:

Here, we tried to create a function that performs linear regression from scratch as explained in the beginning of this chapter by implementing $\beta$ and $R^{2}$, the idea was to compare this created function with the function from the library sklearn. Note that our function is not generalised for the case where we have a BIAS, it means that it makes NO SENSE apply our created function to a biased dataset with mean different of zero

In [24]:
# Function that calculates the Linear regression model when we do not have a linear coefficient

def LinearReg(X,Y):  
    from numpy.linalg import inv
    '''We have: 
       N = Number of points
       p = Number of features
       X = Matrix of measurement of features (size N x p)
       Y = Matrix of answer/target that we want to achieve for the previous features (size N x 1)
       OBS: In this model, we cannot have a linear coefficient, it means that, we MUST normalize X and Y sets to mean 0
       '''
    X_star = inv((X.T)@X)@(X.T)
    Beta = X_star@Y
    R_squared = (1 - (((Y - X@Beta)**2).mean(0))/(Y**2).mean(0)).squeeze()
    return Beta, R_squared

We tried to realize a sanity check, with a simple array, using OUR FUNCTION and SKLEARN. OBS: Again, we must use a dataset that has mean 0, this is very important, our model does not consider a bias

# Let's test our function and compare with something that is already implemented in Python sklearn
# Simple multivariable linear regression in sklearn

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

X = np.array([[-.5, -1], [-.5, 0], [.5, 0], [.5, 1]])     # 4 x 2

y = np.array([[6], [8], [9], [11]]) - 8.5                # 4 X 1
reg = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=False).fit(X, y)

print('For the SKLEARN regression:')
print('The coefficients for the regression are:')
print(reg.coef_.T)
print('The R² value is:')
print(reg.score(X, y))
print('#####################################################')

# Simple multivariable linear regression with our function

Beta, R_squared= LinearReg(X,y)
print('For OUR FUNCTION:')
print('The coefficients for the regression are:')
print(Beta)
print('The R² value is:')
print(R_squared)

D. Lasso regression and model selection¶

Here we want to select a few features as good predictors of quality. For this, we will implement the lasso regression. Lasso performs a so called L1 regularization (a process of introducing additional information in order to prevent overfitting), i.e. adds penalty equivalent to absolute value of the magnitude of coefficients. In the lasso regression, the minimization objective is:

$$ min_{\beta}[ \frac{1}{N}(\sum_{i=1}^N y_{i} - \sum_{j}^p \beta_{j=1} x_{ij})^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_{j}|] $$

for different values of $ \lambda $. First, let's indicate some useful initial values. We will divide the initial dataset in two subsets: a training set of size N = 500 and a test set of size 951 containing the rest of the samples.

To find the best lambda that minimizes our problem, we will implement K-fold cross-validation of lasso regression (model with iterative fitting along a regularization path that select the best model by cross-validation.). To find the best lambda, we make an average of all mse (10) and look for the lambda that gives the lowest value of the mean squared error.We use scikit learn again:

For the classification task, we tried to use the following model that will be briefly explained:

  • Very simple neural network through a supervisioned model, we could say that our model is the beginning of Deep Learning.
  • Our model had 11 inputs (all the features) and only 1 output, the quality that we were trying to predict.

  • From the inputs to the output, we used a non-linearity known as $\textbf{Logistic Regression or Sigmoide Function}.$

  • We used the pytorch library that is normally used for Deep Learning to apply the whole process that will be explained.

The logistic regression model defines a linear separation in the input space.

Let $\mathbf{x}$ be a vector in 2D for instance. The sigmoide computes the probability of the class $c=1$ as

$$ P(c=1|\mathbf{x}) = \sigma (\mathbf{w}^t\mathbf{x}+b) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-(\mathbf{w}^t\mathbf{x}+b)}} $$

The parameters of the model, $\boldsymbol{\theta} = (\mathbf{w},b)$, are learnt from the training data, by minimizing the loss function.

To train such model, we needed different functions that are already implemented on pytorch:

  • the inference for the logistic regression
  • the computation of the loss function
  • the gradient of the loss function w.r.t the parameters
  • the backpropagation of the information

To use this model, we need to separate the features from what we are trying to predict, for us:

  • $x_{train}$ is the training features.
  • $y_{train}$ is the training type of wine (0 or 1, this is the real value, the type of value that should be predicted but in this case, this will improve or model through training).
  • $x_{test}$ is the testing features that will be used after that our model is already trained.
  • $y_{test}$ is the testing type of wine (0 or 1, this is the real value, the type of value that should be predicted and will be used to test the accuracy of our model).

We are now going to define our train function that will be used along the classification task, note that this algorithm is a very classic algorithm that are oftenly used in Deep Learning environments and something related with this model was previously used by us through the Deep Learning course. However, the whole thinking process, programming logic and data treatment are uniques. We also profited from this same algorithm that we constructed here to the famous Titanic Problem disponible in Kaggle.

The $\textbf{training process}$ is given by:

  • $\textbf{Mini-batching}$

    • When training data, one effective technique is to split the whole set into small batches, each batch is called as a minibatch
    • Suppose that the training data has 5000 points, and that the size of a minibatch (what we call batch size) is set to 50. Then there will be 100 minibatches.
    • This is used because when we are dealing with very high amount of data it would be impossible to train your network due to computational limitations.

  • $\textbf{Multiple epochs (first loop)}$

    • During one epoch, EVERY training example that we created is seen ONCE by the model

  • $\textbf{Looping over each training example (second loop)}$

    • Here we apply the optimizer which applies a gradient. The optimizer trains models faster, but it also try to avoid from getting stuck in a local minima. An important parameter that is taken into account by the optimizer is the learning rate, the learning rate is how much we moves through each iteration. This learning rate cannot be neither very small (higher chance to get local minimas) neither very big (high chance of diverging). There is a compromise between learning rate and convergence of our model.
    • We pass through our model, in our case we have $\textbf{11 inputs (features) -> Sigmoide Function -> 1 output (type of wine)}$
    • The loss function is applied. Note that the loss function DEFINES our model, it means, if our model is a classification, if it is a regression, etc. We used the $\textbf{BCELoss}$ that is known as the Binary Cross Entropy, it is only a binary version of the classical cross entropy loss function that is often used for classification tasks.
    • The backpropagation is applied.

The $\textbf{testing process}$ is given by:

  • $\textbf{Stop asking for gradient}$
    • When working with tensors in pytorch we can stop asking for the gradients so the speed of the process will be increased.
  • $\textbf{We re-set the features and the type of wine labels for the testing data.}$
    • Now that our model is already trained, we apply our model to its new features that were NEVER SEEN before.
    • The model will predict something.
    • Note that, as we passes through a logistic regression function, our prevision will be a number between 0 and 1. What we did was to choose 0.5 as the threshold, it means: if $ Model > 0.5 $ we set it as 1 $\textbf{(RED WINE)}$, if $Model <0.5 $ we set it as 0 $\textbf{(WHITE WINE)}$.
    • We calculate the errors and accuracy.
In [49]:
# Function to train our whole model

def train(model,optimizer,loss_fn,epochs,batch_size,Xtrain,Ytrain,Xvalid,Yvalid,verbose=False):
    
    
    ########################################### TRAINING PROCESS ###############################################    
    
    ### Mini-batching
    
    Ntrain = x_train.shape[0]
    Nvalid = x_test.shape[0]
    idx = np.arange(Ntrain)         # idx stores the indices of training examples
    nbatch = int(Ntrain/batch_size)
    
    
    train_losses,valid_losses, valid_accuracies=[],[],[]
 
    for e in range(epochs):
        
         # Randomize the order     
        
        np.random.shuffle(idx)
        running_loss=0
        totaln = 0
        
        # loop over each example 
        
        for bi in range(nbatch):
            
            ids = idx[bi*batch_size:(bi+1)*batch_size]
            features = x_train[ids]      # The 11 inputs that will be used to predict
            type_wine = y_train[ids]     # the associated good answer
            totaln += type_wine.shape[0] # the number of samples
            optimizer.zero_grad()        # The optimizer
            logprobs=model(features)     # The model that we'll apply
            loss=loss_fn(logprobs,type_wine) # The loss function
            loss.backward()                  # The backpropagation
            optimizer.step()            
            running_loss+=loss.item()
            
            
        # training is over for one epoch, it gets back to the first loop and start again
        # now compute interesting quantities to evaluate our model
        accuracy=0
        valid_loss = 0 
        
    ################################### TESTING PROCESS ######################################
    
        with th.no_grad(): # From here, we ignore the gradient in calculations with tensors, which will increase the speed of the code
            features = x_test   # We are going to valid the model
            type_wine = y_test
            logprobs=model(features) # passes the new features never seen before through our trained model
            newlogprobs=logprobs     # just to 
            
            # function that will calculate the accuracy for this specific model, the threshold here is 0.5 for the logistic regression function
            
            for vriu in range(len(logprobs)):
                if logprobs[vriu,0]>=0.5:
                    newlogprobs[vriu,0]=1
                else:
                    newlogprobs[vriu,0]=0
                if newlogprobs[vriu,0]==type_wine[vriu]:
                    accuracy=accuracy+1
            valid_loss=loss_fn(logprobs,type_wine)
        train_losses.append(running_loss/nbatch)
        valid_losses.append(valid_loss)
        valid_accuracies.append(accuracy*100.0/Nvalid)
    
    
        print("Epoch: {}\t".format(e),"training Loss: {:.5f}.. ".format(train_losses[-1]), "validation Loss: {:.5f}.. ".format(valid_losses[-1]),"validation Accuracy: {:.3f}".format(valid_accuracies[-1]))  
    print("---------- Best : {:.3f}".format(max(valid_accuracies)), " at epoch " , np.fromiter(valid_accuracies, dtype=np.float).argmax(), " / ",epochs )
    
    
    # Plotting the graphics
    axes = plt.gca()
    plt.plot(train_losses)
    axes.set_ylim(bottom=0)
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Training losses')
    plt.show()
    plt.plot(valid_losses)
    axes.set_ylim(bottom=0)
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Validation losses')
    plt.show()
    plt.plot(valid_accuracies)
    axes.set_ylim(bottom=90,top=100) 
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Validation accuracy')
    plt.show()

Firstly, it is very important to state that characteristics of the model such as the number of epochs, the batch size and the learning rate can be chosen arbitrarly by the user. We could have tested various combinations of these values that could improve or decrease the algorithm performance by decreasing overfitting phenomena and avoiding local minimas, but for shortening reason and for educational purposes, we just showed how our algorithm works for a specific value of this parameters, as seen before, we chose:

  • Epochs = 500
  • Batch size = 20
  • Learning Rate = 0.001

As we can see from the first $\textbf{Graphic of Training Losses}$, the tendency of this kind of loss is always to decrease because we are learning from these own values and predictions. However, the fact that our training losses keep decreasing is not always a good sign. For example, if the number of epochs is very elevated, what can happens is that we may find a problem called overfitting, where our modelled over-learned from the training data.

About the $\textbf{Graphic of Validation Losses}$, it is normally the graphic where we can observe overfitting processes. When we have this phenomena, the validation losses stop of decreasing and begin to increase again for a given high epoch number. In our specific case we cannot see this phenomena. Nonetheless, around 200/300 epochs we can see that the validation losses do not decrease as it was doing before; it may be an indicative that we can stop around this number of epochs to avoid unnecessary computational calculations. It is common that programmers define a dropline based on the validation losses to avoid overfitting.

The $\textbf{Accuracy Graphic}$ shows us how accurate our trained algorithm is when applied to the testing dataset, it means, testing our model with data that our model never saw before and evaluate how it performs by predicting a result that is known beforehand (supervisioned learning).

Our algorithm got the best accuracy of $\textbf{99.436%}$ at the $\textbf{epoch 335 / 500}$. We are able to see the powerfullness of Machine Learning/Deep Learning networks. Using a very simple model with ONLY a logistic regression function we were able to get a very high accuracy of almost 100%, even though we used ALL the features and realized a very simple pre-treatment of the dataset. We know very well that not necessarily the 11 features are correlated with the type of wine, we could had performed a regression and PCA beforehand. For more complicated datasets this pre-treatement of the data MUST be realized and normally is essential around machine learning and deep learning models
